    "Life can get tough sometimes. With all the pressures we face in our society, it’s understandable that we feel overwhelmed, down, or frustrated as we try to navigate simply from one day to the next. However, as we begin to feel these pressures and emotions, it is important that we take the time to put things into perspective. Jesus, in whose authority we rightly trust, gives us the answer to all such matters when He tells us, “Therefore I say to you, do not worry about your life, what you will eat; nor about the body, what you will put on. Life is more than food, and the body is more than clothing. Consider the ravens, for they neither sow nor reap, which have neither storehouse nor barn; and God feeds them. Of how much more value are you than the birds? And which of you by worrying can add one cubit to his stature? If you then are not able to do the least, why are you anxious for the rest? Consider the lilies, how they grow: they neither toil nor spin; and yet I say to you, even Solomon in all his glory was not arrayed like one of these. If then God so clothes the grass, which today is in the field and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, how much more will He clothe you, O you of little faith? And do not seek what you should eat or what you should drink, nor have an anxious mind. For all these things the nations of the world seek after, and your Father knows that you need these things. But seek the kingdom of God, and all these things shall be added to you. Do not fear, little flock, for it is your Father’s good pleasure to give you the kingdom.”
Luke 12:22-32 (NKJV)
I know it occasionally feels that the world is “winning.” It feels like nothing is going right and everyone and everything is working against us, but if we keep our eyes on Jesus and keep it all in perspective, most of the things we allow to cause us worry and strife are not worth the mental energy we give them. It’s important for us to take each thing as it comes, knowing that it is all in the Father’s hands.
